📊 Statistical Sample Size Formula

This tool uses an attribute sampling formula based on the hypergeometric distribution, commonly used in audit sampling. The sample size is calculated as:

n =
N · p · (1 - p) · Z2
(N - 1) · E2 + p · (1 - p) · Z2

Variable Definitions:

n Required Sample Size - The calculated number of items to select from the population to achieve the desired statistical precision.
N Population Size - The total number of items in the population from which the sample will be drawn.
p Expected Error Rate - The anticipated proportion of errors in the population (default: 1% or 0.01). A higher expected error rate results in a larger sample size.
Z Z-Score (Critical Value) - The standard normal distribution value corresponding to the desired confidence level. Common values: 1.645 (90%), 1.96 (95%), 2.576 (99%).
E Tolerable Error Rate (Precision) - The maximum acceptable margin of error or tolerable deviation rate (default: 5% or 0.05). A smaller tolerable error requires a larger sample.

The formula incorporates a finite population correction factor through the (N-1) term in the denominator, which reduces the required sample size when sampling a significant portion of a finite population.

⚙ How the Tool Operates

Step 1 - Load Data: Upload an Excel file containing your population data. The tool reads all rows and columns, detecting the available fields for stratification.

Step 2 - Configure Sampling: Select your sampling method and parameters:

  • Statistical: Calculates sample size using the formula above based on confidence level, tolerable error, and expected error rate.
  • Simple Random: Randomly selects records based on a fixed sample size or percentage.
  • Percentage: Selects a specified percentage of the population.
  • Systematic: Selects every nth record based on a calculated or specified interval.

Step 3 - Stratification (Optional): Select one or more fields to stratify by. The tool allocates sample counts proportionally to each stratum based on population distribution.

Step 4 - Plan & Adjust: Review the planned allocation. You can manually adjust stratum allocations if needed (requires justification).

Step 5 - Generate & Download: Execute the sampling and download results as Excel or JSON summary.

⚠ When Justification is Required

Override justification is required whenever you deviate from the statistically calculated values. The following table outlines when documentation is needed:

Override Type When It Applies Justification Required
Population Size Override When you manually set a population size different from the loaded data Yes - explain why the override population is appropriate
Sample Size Override When you specify a fixed sample size instead of using the calculated value Yes - justify why the override size meets audit objectives
Sample Percentage Override When you specify a percentage rather than using statistical calculation Yes - document rationale for the selected percentage
Systematic Step Override When you manually set the sampling interval Yes - explain the basis for the interval selection
Stratum Allocation Adjustment When you modify the proportionally allocated sample counts per stratum Yes - document why the adjusted allocation is appropriate
Coverage Override (+1 to empty strata) When adding minimum representation to strata that would otherwise have zero samples Yes - explain the need for coverage of these strata

📝 Best Practices

  • Always document your sampling rationale in the override justification field when using any overrides.
  • The JSON summary contains complete audit trail information including all parameters, allocations, and justifications.
  • For reproducibility, note the random seed used (default: 42). The same seed with identical data will produce identical samples.
  • Review the per-stratum allocation before generating to ensure adequate coverage of all relevant categories.
  • When stratifying, consider whether proportional allocation makes sense for your audit objectives, or if certain strata need enhanced coverage.
